geneVariantDescriptions.description: MET G1163R lies within the protein kinase domain of the Met protein (UniProt.org). G1163R has been described as a secondary drug resistance mutation due to its inability to bind some Met inhibitors (PMID: 21697284, PMID: 28765324, PMID: 31388026), but has not been biochemically characterized and therefore, its effect on Met protein function is unknown (PubMed, Mar 2020).

references.title: A drug resistance screen using a selective MET inhibitor reveals a spectrum of mutations that partially overlap with activating mutations found in cancer patients.
Molecular Modeling of ALK L1198F and/or G1202R Mutations to Determine Differential Crizotinib Sensitivity.
Glesatinib Exhibits Antitumor Activity in Lung Cancer Models and Patients Harboring MET Exon 14 Mutations and Overcomes Mutation-mediated Resistance to Type I MET Inhibitors in Nonclinical Models.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a clinical case study, a lung adenocarcinoma patient harboring MET deletion exon 14 and MET amplification demonstrated resistance to Xalkori (crizotinib), and the patient was found to have acquired MET Y1230H, MET D1228N, MET Y1230S, and MET G1163R (PMID: 28765324).

references.title: Glesatinib Exhibits Antitumor Activity in Lung Cancer Models and Patients Harboring MET Exon 14 Mutations and Overcomes Mutation-mediated Resistance to Type I MET Inhibitors in Nonclinical Models.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a clinical case study, a patient with lung adenocarcinoma harboring MET deletion exon 14 responded to Xalkori (crizotinib), demonstrating a near complete response at 3 months, however, after 9 months progression ensued and a re-biospy identified MET del exon14, MET amplification, MET D1228N, MET Y1230H, MET Y1230S, and MET G1163R (PMID: 28522754).

references.title: MET Exon 14 Mutation Encodes an Actionable Therapeutic Target in Lung Adenocarcinoma.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a clinical case study, a lung adenocarcinoma patient previously harboring MET amp, MET deletion exon 14, MET D1228N, MET Y1230H, MET Y1230S, and MET G1163R demonstrated a decrease in lesion size when treated with Glesatinib (MGCD265), however, progression ensued and plasma testing indicated the patient lost Y1230H and Y1230S, but acquired MET L1195V (PMID: 28765324).
